e 敖, meaning both ‘rambling’ and ‘deposed king without posthumous titles’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the personal name of <i>Tai Ao</i> (太敖), teacher of the legendary king Zhuanxu (traditional dates: 2514–2437  BC ). (ii) it is said that the surname is also borne by descendants of deposed kings of the former state of Chu, with no posthumous titles, during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC )."]},{"name":"Auer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Matthias, Siegfried, Bernd, Bernhard, Erna, Franz, Fritz, Hermann, Horst.","German (mainly Bavaria): topographic name for someone living by a water meadow, German <i>Au</i>, or a habitational name for someone from a place called Au or Aue (see   Au   and   Aue  ). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine), Czechia, and Slovenia."]}]},{"name":"Einion","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: originally a byname meaning ‘anvil’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Einion ap Llywarch was born about 1165, in Carmarthenshire, Wales, his father, Lloarch Ap Kynhathwye Lord of Kidwelly, was 40 and his mother, Lloarch ap Klow Kidwelly, was 22. He married Ann ferch Llywelyn in 1149, in Carmarthenshire, Wales. They were the parents of at least 7 sons. He died from about 1142 to 1197, in Wales."},"et":{"about 1165–WFT Est. 1142-1197":"umbes 1165–umbes 1142 kuni 1197","1165–1197":"1165–1197","1105–1164":"1105–1164","1155–Female":"1155–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1195–1206":"1195–1206","–Male":"Surnud","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1164–1235":"1164–1235","1166–Male":"1166–Surnud","1168–Male":"1168–Surnud","1127–1170":"1127–1170","1145–Female":"1145–Surnud","WFT Est. 1142-1197":"umbes 1142 kuni 1197","1165":"1165","1164":"1164","1197":"1197","1195":"1195","1161":"1161","1170":"1170","1206":"1206","1127":"1127","1105":"1105","1235":"1235","1168":"1168","1145":"1145","1166":"1166","